<subSubSection id="C31B653AFFE07D612AD3FE9C6059FCA4" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BBE36B1FFE07D612AD3FE9C611FFDAD" blockId="46.[151,1436,151,815]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D612AD3FE9C647EFEE6" bold="true" box="[197,325,338,364]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C014D32FFE07D612B59FE9C6700FEE1" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1869" box="[335,571,338,363]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="hebes">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D612B59FE9C6700FEE1" box="[335,571,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Leptogorgia hebes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very common species in the shallow SAB and can be found on hardbottom environments along with 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D32FFE07D612840FEB66656FE1B" baseAuthorityName="Kolliker" baseAuthorityYear="1865" box="[598,877,376,401]" class="Anthozoa" family="Spongiodermidae" genus="Titanideum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="frauenfeldii">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D612840FEB66656FE1B" box="[598,877,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Titanideum frauenfeldii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D32FFE07D6129BEFEB66197FE1B" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1815" box="[936,1196,376,401]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="virgulata">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D6129BEFEB66197FE1B" box="[936,1196,376,401]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Leptogorgia virgulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The colonies reach moderate size and are irregularly pinnately branched in one plane or slightly bushy. The polyp mounds are hemispherical near the main branch and less distinct near the ends of the twigs, and the apertures are slit-like. There is often a distinct groove that runs down two sides of the slightly flattened branches. Terminal twigs are 
<quantity id="4CF99B54FFE07D612A81FDC365C3FDAD" box="[151,248,525,551]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 mm</quantity>
in diameter while branches near the colony base may be up to 
<quantity id="4CF99B54FFE07D6129CFFDC3611BFDAD" box="[985,1056,525,551]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBE36B1FFE07D612AD3FDFC6138FD36" blockId="46.[151,1436,151,815]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
The coenenchymal sclerites are blunt capstans and 8-radiates up to 0.1 mm, and the polyps have flattened serrated rods of approximately the same size. 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D32FFE07D6128A4FD96662FFDFB" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1869" box="[690,788,600,625]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="hebes">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D6128A4FD96662FFDFB" box="[690,788,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">L. hebes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually bright red, orange or dark yellow, but purple colonies have been recorded (
<bibRefCitation id="EF904B40FFE07D612832FDB367F8FD1D" author="Bayer, F. M." box="[548,707,637,663]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="1 - 373" refId="ref24655" refString="Bayer, F. M. (1961) The shallow-water Octocorallia of the West Indian region. A manual for marine biologists. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands, 12, 1 - 373." type="journal article" year="1961">Bayer 1961</bibRefCitation>
). This species has been observed with numerous small gorgonocephalid ophiuroids attached to its branches (DeVictor, pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBE36B1FFE07D612AD3FD066175FD68" blockId="46.[151,1436,151,815]" box="[197,1102,712,738]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">There are numerous lots of this species in the NMNH from the shallow SAB.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBE36B1FFE07D612AD0FD236059FCA4" blockId="46.[151,1436,151,815]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B975EAA3FFE07D612AD0FD2364EFFC8D" bold="true" box="[198,468,749,775]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Atlantic distribution:</emphasis>
Virginia to north Florida, 
<quantity id="4CF99B54FFE07D61290FFD2366BDFC8D" box="[793,902,749,775]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" metricValueMax="11.6" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="m" value="62.0" valueMax="116.0" valueMin="8.0">8–116 m</quantity>
; Gulf of Mexico, 
<quantity id="4CF99B54FFE07D612E73FD2361FFFC8D" box="[1125,1220,749,775]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="m" value="18.5" valueMax="37.0" valueMin="0.0">0–37 m</quantity>
; 
<collectingCountry id="F3167621FFE07D612EC2FD23601BFC8D" box="[1236,1312,749,775]" name="Aruba" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Aruba</collectingCountry>
, unknown depth; 
<collectingCountry id="F3167621FFE07D612AF1FCDB6414FCA5" box="[231,303,789,815]" name="Brazil" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(unknown depth) (
<bibRefCitation id="EF904B40FFE07D612818FCDB67DFFCA5" author="Deichmann, E." box="[526,740,789,815]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" refId="ref25431" refString="Deichmann, E. (1936) The Alcyonaria of the western part of the Atlantic Ocean. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 53, 317 pp." type="book" year="1936">Deichmann, 1936</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF904B40FFE07D6128E6FCDB66BAFCA5" author="Bayer, F. M." box="[752,897,789,815]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="1 - 373" refId="ref24655" refString="Bayer, F. M. (1961) The shallow-water Octocorallia of the West Indian region. A manual for marine biologists. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands, 12, 1 - 373." type="journal article" year="1961">Bayer, 1961</bibRefCitation>
; NMNH collections; SERTC collection).
</paragraph>
